## What is _specification pattern_?

> The **specification pattern** is a particular software design pattern, whereby **business rules** can be **recombined** by chaining the business rules together using boolean logic.
> -- <cite>[Wikipedia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Specification_pattern)</cite>

Concretely, instead to implement rules using `if`/`else` like:
```java
if (!product.isDangerous() && (product.getColor().equals("black") || product.getAmount() > 100))
    result = true;
```
the rules are implemented **unitary** and **combined** to produce the final rule:
```java
Rule isDangerous, isBlack, amountGreaterThan100 = ...;
Rule combined = isDangerous.not().and( isBlack.or(amountGreaterThan100) );
result = combined.test(product);
```

## Lack of dynamism

The _specification pattern_ allow to produce readable and maintainable code, but it is **static**: you have to update/compile/deploy application to change business rules.

This application _solves this problem_, by...
1. defining **combination** of rules **into** simple **database**;
2. proposing **admin UI** to manage theses rules.
